
TECHNICAL REQUIREMENTS DOCUMENT

Canvas Assignment Dashboard
Mac Menu Bar App

Version	1.0 — Draft
Date	April 2026
Author	Aarav Chhabra
Status	In Review
Based on	Canvas Dashboard PRD v1.0

This document translates the Canvas Dashboard PRD into concrete technical decisions, system architecture, API contracts, and implementation specifications for the macOS menu bar application.
 
1. System Overview
The Canvas Assignment Dashboard is a native-feeling macOS utility that periodically fetches assignment data from the UW Canvas LMS and surfaces it passively in the menu bar. The app runs as a background process, auto-starts on login, and renders a dropdown panel on click.

1.1 Architecture Summary
The app is structured as three loosely coupled layers:

Layer	Responsibility
Data layer	Canvas API / iCal sync, caching, background refresh scheduling
State layer	In-memory assignment store, urgency bucketing, course metadata
UI layer	Menu bar icon, dropdown panel, macOS notifications, settings window

1.2 Technology Stack
Component	Choice & Rationale
Runtime	Electron 30 + Node.js 20 LTS — fastest path to a working app using web tech; avoids Swift learning curve for MVP
UI framework	React 18 + TypeScript — typed component model, good ecosystem, fast iteration
Styling	Tailwind CSS — utility classes, no CSS file sprawl
Build tool	Vite + electron-vite — fast HMR in dev, tree-shaking for prod
Packaging	electron-builder — produces .dmg installer and .app bundle
Credential storage	keytar (native Keychain bridge) — stores Canvas token securely
HTTP client	Axios — interceptors for rate limiting, retry logic
iCal parser	ical.js — RFC 5545 compliant, well-maintained
Scheduling	node-cron + Electron wake events — drives background syncs
Persistence	electron-store (JSON on disk) — settings, course colors, cached data
Notifications	Electron's Notification API (wraps macOS UNUserNotificationCenter)
Testing	Vitest (unit), Playwright (e2e Electron)

1.3 Non-Functional Requirements
Requirement	Target
Startup time (cold)	< 3 seconds to menu bar icon visible
Sync latency on wake	First refresh completes within 10 seconds of wake event
Memory footprint	< 120 MB RAM at steady state (Electron baseline ~80 MB)
CPU usage (idle)	< 1% CPU between sync cycles
Disk usage	< 250 MB installed (including Electron runtime)
API rate limit compliance	Never poll Canvas REST API more than once per 5 minutes
Token security	Canvas token stored only in macOS Keychain; never written to disk in plaintext
macOS compatibility	macOS 13 Ventura and later (Electron 30 minimum)
Offline behavior	App remains functional with stale cached data when network is unavailable; shows last-sync timestamp
 
2. Canvas API Integration
2.1 Authentication
The app uses a Canvas Personal Access Token (PAT). The user generates this once inside Canvas (Account > Settings > Approved Integrations > New Access Token). The token is stored in macOS Keychain via keytar and retrieved at runtime — it is never written to disk or logged.

keytar.setPassword('canvas-dashboard', 'canvas-token', token)
const token = await keytar.getPassword('canvas-dashboard', 'canvas-token')

2.2 Base URL Configuration
The Canvas instance URL is user-configurable (defaults to https://canvas.uw.edu). Stored in electron-store under settings.canvasBaseUrl. All API calls are prefixed with this URL.

2.3 REST API Endpoints
The following Canvas REST API endpoints are used. All require Authorization: Bearer <token> header.

Endpoint	Used for	Refresh interval
GET /api/v1/courses?enrollment_state=active	Fetch active courses and metadata	On launch + hourly
GET /api/v1/planner/items?per_page=50&start_date=<now>	Unified assignment/quiz/discussion feed	Every 30 min + on wake
GET /api/v1/courses/:id/assignments?bucket=upcoming	Per-course assignment detail fallback	On demand
GET /api/v1/users/self/upcoming_events	Upcoming events (alternative planner view)	Every 30 min

2.4 iCal Feed (MVP Path)
For the initial MVP, the app can use the Canvas calendar iCal feed instead of the REST API. The user pastes their feed URL (found at Canvas > Calendar > Calendar Feed). This avoids token setup friction but loses submission status.

https://canvas.uw.edu/feeds/calendars/user_<hash>.ics

The iCal feed is fetched with a plain HTTP GET (no auth required). Parsed with ical.js. Events with DTSTART within the lookahead window are surfaced as assignments. SUMMARY maps to assignment title; DESCRIPTION may include course name and a Canvas link.

2.5 Rate Limiting & Error Handling
Scenario	Handling
HTTP 403 / 401	Clear stored token, show re-auth prompt in settings panel
HTTP 429 (rate limited)	Exponential backoff: wait 60s, 120s, 240s before retry; show warning badge
HTTP 5xx	Retry up to 3 times with 10s delay; fall back to cached data; log error
Network offline	Skip sync cycle; display 'Offline — showing cached data' in panel footer
iCal parse error	Log malformed event, skip it, continue parsing rest of feed
Token missing	Block sync; show onboarding prompt; never crash
 
3. Data Model
3.1 Assignment Object
The canonical in-memory assignment object used across the app:

interface Assignment {
  id: string                    // Canvas assignment ID or iCal UID
  title: string                 // Assignment name
  courseId: string
  courseName: string
  courseColor: string           // Hex color, user-configurable
  dueAt: Date | null            // null = no due date
  type: 'assignment' | 'quiz' | 'discussion' | 'announcement'
  submissionState: 'submitted' | 'unsubmitted' | 'graded' | 'unknown'
  pointsPossible: number | null
  canvasUrl: string             // Direct link to assignment page
  isOverdue: boolean            // dueAt < now && not submitted
  source: 'rest' | 'ical'       // Where data originated
}

3.2 Urgency Buckets
Assignments are bucketed at render time based on dueAt relative to the current timestamp:

Bucket	Condition
Overdue	dueAt < now && submissionState !== 'submitted'
Due today	dueAt is between now and end of today (midnight)
Due tomorrow	dueAt falls on the next calendar day
This week	dueAt within 7 days but not today or tomorrow
Coming up	dueAt > 7 days from now (shown up to lookahead window setting)
No due date	dueAt is null — shown at bottom with muted treatment

3.3 Persistence (electron-store)
The following keys are persisted to disk using electron-store (JSON file in the app's userData directory):

Key	Contents
settings.canvasBaseUrl	Canvas instance URL string
settings.syncIntervalMinutes	Number (default: 30)
settings.lookaheadDays	Number (default: 14)
settings.notificationLeadTimes	Array of minutes before due date to fire notification
courses	Array of Course objects (id, name, color, hidden)
assignmentsCache	Array of Assignment objects from last successful sync
lastSyncAt	ISO timestamp string
onboardingComplete	Boolean

The Canvas token is NOT stored here — it lives exclusively in macOS Keychain.
 
4. Background Sync Engine
4.1 Sync Triggers
Trigger	Implementation
App launch	Sync fires immediately after startup, before first render
Timer (every N minutes)	node-cron job running in main process; interval from settings.syncIntervalMinutes
macOS wake from sleep	Electron powerMonitor 'resume' event triggers immediate sync
Manual refresh	User clicks refresh icon in panel; fires ad-hoc sync
Settings change	Changing canvas URL or token triggers immediate re-sync

4.2 Sync Flow
Each sync cycle follows this sequence:

•	Set syncStatus = 'syncing'; update tray icon to spinner variant
•	Fetch active courses via GET /api/v1/courses
•	Fetch planner items via GET /api/v1/planner/items (paginated, up to lookahead window)
•	Merge new data with existing cache: additions and updates applied, removals flagged
•	Re-run urgency bucketing on merged dataset
•	Persist updated cache and lastSyncAt to electron-store
•	Emit 'assignments-updated' IPC event to renderer process
•	Check notification queue: fire any notifications due since last sync
•	Set syncStatus = 'idle'; restore tray icon

4.3 IPC Architecture
Electron's contextBridge and ipcMain/ipcRenderer are used for all main-to-renderer communication. The renderer never has direct Node.js access (contextIsolation: true, nodeIntegration: false).

IPC Channel	Direction & Purpose
assignments:get	Renderer → Main: request current assignment list
assignments:data	Main → Renderer: push updated assignment list after sync
sync:trigger	Renderer → Main: manual refresh request
sync:status	Main → Renderer: push sync status ('idle' | 'syncing' | 'error')
settings:get	Renderer → Main: read settings
settings:set	Renderer → Main: write settings
token:save	Renderer → Main: store token in Keychain
token:check	Renderer → Main: check if token exists (returns boolean, never the token itself)
 
5. UI & Window Specification
5.1 Menu Bar Icon
State	Icon treatment
Idle (assignments exist)	Calendar glyph with count badge (number of items due today/overdue)
Idle (nothing due today)	Calendar glyph, no badge
Syncing	Animated spinner (16x16 PNG sequence at 10fps via Tray.setImage)
Error / offline	Icon with small warning dot (amber)
Overdue items exist	Badge rendered in red background

Icon assets: 16x16 and 32x32 PNG (for Retina). Template images (black/white) so macOS auto-inverts for dark menu bars. Stored in resources/icons/.

5.2 Dropdown Panel
•	Window type: BrowserWindow with frame: false, alwaysOnTop: false, show: false; positioned below tray icon using tray.getBounds()
•	Size: 340px wide, height dynamic (min 240px, max 560px); uses auto-height via IPC after render
•	Vibrancy: vibrancy: 'under-window', visualEffectState: 'active' on macOS for frosted glass background
•	Dismissal: clicking outside the panel closes it (window blur event); pressing Escape closes it
•	Sections rendered top to bottom: header bar (app name + sync status + settings gear), then urgency buckets, then footer (last synced timestamp + manual refresh)

5.3 Assignment Row Component
Each assignment renders as a single row (height 44px) containing:

•	Course color dot (8px circle, left edge)
•	Assignment title (truncated with ellipsis at 180px max-width)
•	Due time string (e.g. 'Today 11:59 PM', 'Tomorrow', 'Apr 28')
•	Submission badge: green checkmark if submitted, red dot if overdue, nothing otherwise
•	Entire row is clickable — opens the Canvas assignment URL in the default browser

5.4 Settings Window
•	Separate BrowserWindow (not the dropdown); opened via gear icon; 480x520px fixed size
•	Fields: Canvas base URL (text input), API token (password input with show/hide toggle), sync interval (select: 15/30/60 min), lookahead days (slider: 7/14/30/quarter), notification lead times (checkbox list: 24h, 2h, 30min, 15min)
•	Course list: rendered below settings; each course shows name, color picker (native color input), and a visibility toggle
•	On save: validates token with a test API call before persisting; shows success/error inline

5.5 Onboarding Flow
Shown once on first launch. Full-window BrowserWindow (560x440px):

•	Step 1: Welcome screen with brief description and 'Get Started' CTA
•	Step 2: Canvas URL input (pre-filled with https://canvas.uw.edu)
•	Step 3: Token input with a direct link to the Canvas token generation page
•	Step 4: Permission request for macOS notifications (calls Notification.requestPermission())
•	Step 5: First sync runs inline; success screen shows count of assignments found
•	Completion: sets onboardingComplete = true in store; opens main dropdown panel
 
6. Notification System
6.1 Notification Logic
After each sync, the notification engine checks for assignments that cross a lead-time threshold between the previous sync and the current time. This prevents duplicate notifications across sync cycles.

for each assignment with dueAt != null:
  for each leadTime in settings.notificationLeadTimes:
    fireAt = dueAt - leadTime (minutes)
    if lastSyncAt < fireAt <= now:
      fire notification for this assignment

6.2 Notification Content
Field	Content
Title	Course name (e.g. 'CSE 123')
Body	Assignment title + 'due in X hours' or 'due in X minutes'
Action button	'Open in Canvas' — calls shell.openExternal(assignment.canvasUrl)
Identifier	assignment.id + leadTime — prevents duplicate system notifications

6.3 Focus Mode Behavior
Electron does not currently expose a native API to read macOS Focus mode state. As a practical workaround, notifications use the default urgency level. Users can suppress them using macOS system-level Focus filters (the app appears in System Settings > Focus > App Exceptions). Document this limitation in the settings UI.
 
7. App Startup & Lifecycle
7.1 Login Item (Auto-Launch)
The app registers itself as a macOS login item using Electron's built-in API:

app.setLoginItemSettings({ openAtLogin: true, openAsHidden: true })

openAsHidden: true means the app starts without opening any window — only the menu bar icon appears. The user can toggle this in the Settings window.

7.2 Main Process Boot Sequence
•	app.whenReady(): create tray icon, register powerMonitor listeners, start sync engine
•	Check onboardingComplete in store; if false, open onboarding window
•	If onboardingComplete, fire initial sync immediately
•	Register IPC handlers (assignments, sync, settings, token)
•	Start node-cron job for scheduled syncs

7.3 Quit Behavior
The app should not quit when all windows are closed (window-all-closed event ignored). It lives in the menu bar permanently. Right-clicking the tray icon exposes a Quit option. On quit, the sync engine is cleanly shut down and caches flushed.
 
8. Security Model
8.1 Token Handling Rules
•	Token is fetched from Keychain once per app session and held in memory in the main process only
•	Token is NEVER sent over IPC to the renderer process
•	Token is NEVER logged (console.log, file log, or Electron crash reporter)
•	Token is NOT included in electron-store persistence
•	If keytar.getPassword returns null, all API calls are blocked until re-auth

8.2 Content Security Policy
The BrowserWindow is configured with a strict CSP to prevent XSS and remote code execution:

Content-Security-Policy:
  default-src 'self';
  script-src 'self';
  style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline';
  connect-src 'self' https://canvas.uw.edu;
  img-src 'self' data:;
  frame-src 'none';

8.3 Electron Security Checklist
Setting	Value
nodeIntegration	false
contextIsolation	true
sandbox	true
webSecurity	true
allowRunningInsecureContent	false
experimentalFeatures	false
preload script	Used for all contextBridge exposure; minimal surface area
 
9. Build & Distribution
9.1 Development Setup
•	Node.js 20 LTS required
•	Install dependencies: npm install
•	Dev server: npm run dev (launches Electron with Vite HMR)
•	Main process changes require manual restart; renderer hot-reloads

9.2 Build & Package
•	Production build: npm run build (Vite bundles renderer; tsc compiles main process)
•	Package: npm run dist (electron-builder produces .app and .dmg in dist/)
•	App bundle size target: < 250 MB

9.3 Code Signing (Future)
For distribution beyond personal use, the app must be signed and notarized with an Apple Developer ID ($99/year). For now, the app is distributed as an unsigned .app with instructions to right-click > Open to bypass Gatekeeper. This is acceptable for personal/single-user use.

9.4 Project Structure
canvas-dashboard/
  src/
    main/              # Electron main process (TS)
      index.ts         # Entry point, app lifecycle
      tray.ts          # Tray icon + menu
      sync.ts          # Canvas API + iCal sync engine
      notifications.ts # Notification scheduling
      ipc.ts           # IPC handler registration
    renderer/          # React app (TSX)
      App.tsx          # Root component
      Panel.tsx        # Dropdown panel
      Settings.tsx     # Settings window
      Onboarding.tsx   # First-run flow
      components/      # AssignmentRow, BucketSection, etc.
    shared/            # Types shared between main + renderer
      types.ts         # Assignment, Course, SyncStatus interfaces
  resources/
    icons/             # Tray icon PNGs (16, 32, template variants)
  electron.vite.config.ts
  electron-builder.yml
  package.json
 
10. Testing Plan
10.1 Unit Tests (Vitest)
•	Urgency bucketing logic: test each bucket boundary condition with fixed timestamps
•	iCal parser: test against sample .ics files including edge cases (all-day events, missing DTSTART, multi-day events)
•	Rate limit backoff: mock axios, verify retry intervals
•	Notification deduplication: verify same assignment + leadTime doesn't fire twice
•	Assignment merge logic: additions, updates, and removals from API response

10.2 Integration Tests
•	Canvas API mock server (nock): simulate 200, 401, 429, 503 responses
•	Keytar mock: verify token is retrieved but never exposed over IPC
•	electron-store: verify correct keys are read/written across settings changes

10.3 Manual QA Checklist
Test case	Expected result
First launch with no token	Onboarding opens; app does not crash or sync
Invalid token entered	API returns 401; settings shows error; no assignments loaded
Network goes offline mid-sync	Sync fails gracefully; stale cache shown with 'Offline' footer
Machine wakes from sleep	Sync fires within 10 seconds; panel reflects fresh data
Assignment becomes overdue	Moves to Overdue bucket on next sync; shown in red
All assignments submitted	Nothing in Overdue/Today buckets; 'All clear' state shown
Notification lead time fires	macOS notification appears with correct assignment title and course
Token deleted from Keychain manually	App detects missing token on next sync; prompts re-auth
 
11. Phased Implementation Plan
Phase 1 — MVP (Weeks 1-3)
•	Electron + Vite + React scaffold with menu bar icon
•	iCal feed fetch and parse (no auth required)
•	Basic urgency bucketing and panel render (Today / This Week / Later)
•	electron-store for settings (Canvas iCal URL, lookahead window)
•	Auto-launch via app.setLoginItemSettings
•	Manual refresh button
•	Unsigned .app bundle via electron-builder

Phase 2 — Full Integration (Weeks 4-5)
•	REST API integration with PAT stored in Keychain via keytar
•	Submission status badges on assignment rows
•	macOS notifications with configurable lead times
•	powerMonitor wake event triggering auto-sync
•	Course color coding and per-course hide toggle
•	Onboarding flow with step-by-step token setup

Phase 3 — Polish (Optional, Weeks 6-7)
•	Vibrancy / frosted glass panel background
•	Personal task layer (local-only manual tasks)
•	Menu bar icon badge count for overdue/today items
•	Settings import/export for easy reinstall
•	Optional: open-source release and README for other UW students
 
12. Open Questions & Decisions
Question	Notes
iCal vs REST API for MVP?	Recommend iCal for speed; REST in Phase 2. Confirm iCal feed lag is acceptable (15-30 min).
Should the panel use vibrancy?	Vibrancy is visually nice but adds complexity and can cause flicker. Defer to Phase 3.
Sync interval default?	30 minutes is proposed. Canvas iCal lags up to 30 min anyway, so syncing more often wastes calls.
Multiple Canvas instances?	Out of scope for v1. One Canvas URL per installation. Could add in v2 for students at multiple schools.
Apple Silicon vs Intel build?	electron-builder supports universal binary. Build as universal from the start.
Crash reporting?	Skip for personal use. If open-sourced, add Sentry with no PII in payloads.
Auto-update?	Out of scope for v1. Manual re-download if needed.

